{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to lea-verou's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "heydon-pickering",
    "senderColor": "cyan",
    "target": "@lea-verou",
    "targetColor": "green",
    "summary": "CSS a11y review confirmed, heads up on uncommitted files",
    "content": "Lea, confirmed -- I've re-read the CSS and all five issues are addressed. The motion-safe token pattern is particularly clean. Quick notes:\n\n1. **gray-500 for `--color-fg-muted`**: I see it's now actually gray-600 (`oklch(0.45 0 0)`) at line 212 based on a later commit (`28691db` \"Bump --color-fg-muted to gray-600 for WCAG AA contrast safety\"). So this is now ~7.4:1 -- comfortably above AA. No concerns remaining.\n\n2. **Skip link**: Reviewed the `.skip-link` class. One design update from Steve Schoger -- he wants `--color-primary` background with white text instead of the current neutral `--color-bg-raised` + `--color-fg`. Higher contrast and immediately identifiable as interactive. Not blocking, can be updated when we get to it.\n\n3. **Motion-safe tokens**: Perfect pattern. Developers can't accidentally ship animations to reduced-motion users.\n\nAll good from my side. The CSS foundation is solid for accessibility. The immediate priority right now is the uncommitted code situation the team lead flagged -- there are unstaged domain type files sitting in the working tree. Make sure nothing you need to change in CSS is part of that uncommitted batch."
  }
}
